	<h3>The "Good Side" Question</h3>
	<p>Avoiding disputes over which side of fence faces which property:</p>

	<p><strong>Traditional Approach (Posts on Your Side):</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Support posts face property of person who paid for fence</li>
		<li>Finished side faces neighbor's property</li>
		<li>Shows courtesy and prevents neighbor complaints</li>
		<li>Standard practice for fences built entirely by one owner</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Modern Alternative (Good Neighbor Fence):</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Fence designed to look good from both sides</li>
		<li>Posts between panels rather than behind them</li>
		<li>Eliminates "good side" vs "bad side" issue entirely</li>
		<li>Facilitates cost sharing and neighbor cooperation</li>
		<li>Typically costs 10-15% more than traditional design</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Shared Cost Agreements:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Specify which side faces which property in written agreement</li>
		<li>Consider alternating directions every X feet for fairness</li>
		<li>Or use good neighbor design and both parties satisfied</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Resolving Active Fence Disputes</h2>

	<h3>Resolution Process Hierarchy</h3>

	<p><strong>Level 1: Direct Negotiation (Try First)</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Approach:</strong> Talk directly with neighbor to find solution</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> Free</li>
		<li><strong>Success rate:</strong> High if both parties reasonable</li>
		<li><strong>Timeline:</strong> Days to weeks</li>
		<li><strong>Best for:</strong> First attempt at any dispute</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Level 2: Mediation (Recommended Next Step)</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Approach:</strong> Neutral third party helps negotiate agreement</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $100-400 per session (often split between parties)</li>
		<li><strong>Success rate:</strong> 70-80% reach agreement</li>
		<li><strong>Timeline:</strong> 1-3 sessions over 2-6 weeks</li>
		<li><strong>Best for:</strong> Complex disputes, strained relations</li>
		<li><strong>Resources:</strong> San Joaquin County Bar Association offers mediator referrals</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Level 3: Small Claims Court (Under $10,000)</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Approach:</strong> Sue for damages or cost recovery</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $30-100 filing fee, no attorney needed</li>
		<li><strong>Success rate:</strong> Varies based on documentation and facts</li>
		<li><strong>Timeline:</strong> 2-4 months from filing to hearing</li>
		<li><strong>Best for:</strong> Clear-cut cases with good documentation</li>
		<li><strong>Limit:</strong> Cannot order fence removal, only money damages</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Level 4: Civil Court (Over $10,000 or Injunctions)</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Approach:</strong> Full lawsuit with attorney representation</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $3,000-15,000+ in attorney fees</li>
		<li><strong>Success rate:</strong> Varies, but costly even if you win</li>
		<li><strong>Timeline:</strong> 6-18+ months from filing to resolution</li>
		<li><strong>Best for:</strong> Serious encroachments, spite fences, large damages</li>
		<li><strong>Powers:</strong> Can order fence removal, issue injunctions</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>When to Involve Attorneys</h3>
	<p>Situations where legal counsel is worthwhile:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Significant money involved:</strong> Disputes over $5,000+ warrant legal advice</li>
		<li><strong>Adverse possession concerns:</strong> Encroachment existed 5+ years</li>
		<li><strong>Easement issues:</strong> Complex property rights questions</li>
		<li><strong>Title problems:</strong> Encroachment affecting property sale</li>
		<li><strong>Spite fence claims:</strong> Proving malicious intent requires legal expertise</li>
		<li><strong>Property damage:</strong> Fence installation or removal caused damage</li>
		<li><strong>Injunction needed:</strong> Must stop neighbor from proceeding with fence work</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Building Fence to Avoid Boundary Issues</h3>
	<p>Conservative approach preventing most disputes:</p>

	<p><strong>The "6-Inch Setback" Strategy:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>What it is:</strong> Build fence 6 inches inside your property line</li>
		<li><strong>Advantages:</strong> Clearly on your property, no neighbor permission needed</li>
		<li><strong>Cost implication:</strong> You pay 100%, neighbor has no say in design</li>
		<li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> Entirely your responsibility</li>
		<li><strong>Access:</strong> You can maintain both sides without entering neighbor's land</li>
		<li><strong>Downside:</strong> Lose 6 inches of yard space around perimeter</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Why This Approach Works:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Eliminates shared fence cost disputes</li>
		<li>No risk of encroachment onto neighbor's property</li>
		<li>You control fence style, height (within codes), maintenance</li>
		<li>Neighbor cannot demand changes or removal</li>
		<li>Survey errors have buffer before causing encroachment</li>
		<li>Future sales cleaner with no shared fence issues</li>
	</ul>

