		<li><strong>Style restrictions:</strong> Fence must match historic character of area</li>
		<li><strong>Material requirements:</strong> May require traditional materials (wood, iron)</li>
		<li><strong>Height considerations:</strong> Historic standards may differ from modern codes</li>
		<li><strong>Neighbor disputes:</strong> All parties must comply with historic rules</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Practical Advice for Stockton Homeowners</h2>

	<h3>Before Building Any Fence</h3>
	<p>Essential checklist to prevent future problems:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Survey your property:</strong> Know exactly where boundaries are</li>
		<li><strong>Check local codes:</strong> Verify height limits, setbacks, permit requirements</li>
		<li><strong>Review HOA rules:</strong> Confirm compliance with community restrictions</li>
		<li><strong>Talk to neighbors:</strong> Discuss plans, especially for boundary fences</li>
		<li><strong>Get written agreements:</strong> Document any cost sharing or design agreements</li>
		<li><strong>Obtain permits:</strong> Get required permits before starting work</li>
		<li><strong>Hire licensed contractor:</strong> Ensure professional, code-compliant installation</li>
		<li><strong>Document everything:</strong> Photos, receipts, agreements, permits</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>If Dispute Arises</h3>
	<p>Steps to take when conflicts emerge:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Stay calm:</strong> Emotional reactions escalate conflicts</li>
		<li><strong>Document situation:</strong> Photos, measurements, written descriptions</li>
		<li><strong>Research your rights:</strong> Understand what law actually requires</li>
		<li><strong>Talk to neighbor:</strong> Many disputes resolve with conversation</li>
		<li><strong>Propose solutions:</strong> Offer reasonable compromises</li>
		<li><strong>Get survey if needed:</strong> Objective facts help resolve boundary disputes</li>
		<li><strong>Try mediation:</strong> Before resorting to legal action</li>
		<li><strong>Consult attorney:</strong> Get legal advice before making major decisions</li>
		<li><strong>Keep records:</strong> All communications, agreements, expenses</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>What NOT to Do</h3>
	<p>Actions that make disputes worse:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Don't remove neighbor's fence:</strong> Even if you think it encroaches (potential criminal charges)</li>
		<li><strong>Don't build without survey:</strong> Guessing boundary location creates liability</li>
		<li><strong>Don't ignore encroachment:</strong> Waiting allows adverse possession claims</li>
		<li><strong>Don't proceed without permits:</strong> Code violations give neighbor ammunition</li>
		<li><strong>Don't make threats:</strong> Threatening language damages your position</li>
		<li><strong>Don't rely on verbal agreements:</strong> Get everything in writing</li>
		<li><strong>Don't assume old fence marks boundary:</strong> Fences often misplaced</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Conclusion: Prevention and Cooperation</h2>

	<p>Most fence disputes are preventable through proper planning, clear communication, and respect for property rights and neighbor relationships. Understanding California fence law empowers you to protect your interests while avoiding unnecessary conflicts that damage both your wallet and your neighborhood harmony.</p>

	<p>The key principles: know your exact property boundaries through professional survey, communicate openly with neighbors before building, get all agreements in writing, follow local codes and obtain required permits, and approach disagreements with willingness to find reasonable compromises.</p>

	<p>When disputes do arise, exhaust negotiation and mediation before resorting to legal action. The cost of litigation - both financial and relational - far exceeds the cost of compromise in most cases. However, know your rights and be prepared to enforce them when neighbors act unreasonably or encroach on your property.</p>

